Modelling amphibian extinction risk

Modelling amphibian extinction risk

Melanie Tietje

Data explanation

The dataset is a mix of data from the Paleobiology Database (accessible via Fossilworks or PaleobioDB), FosFARbase and lots of literature research. It contains coordinates, count data and also factorial variables.

Variable definitions

variable name details
species the binomial species name
order the taxonomic order of the species
ma_range duration the species covered in the fossil record in million years
mni_max minimum number of individuals in one location, maximum value for each species
spec_max maximum number of specimens in one location, maximum value for each species
grid_cells number of grid cells a species occupies
gcd maximum great circle distance; shortest connection between two points on the surface of a sphere
lat_range maximum latitudinal range of a species (maximum difference between paleolatitudes)
mean_lat mean latitude calculated from all species occurrences
min_lat minimum latitude
hab.cat.b habitat category; low, high, or highlow (last one meaning both). Distinguished basically between flowing and stagnant water bodies
habitat_width number of habitats utilized by the species
asl_pred maximum or only available skull length; values scaled from 0 to 1
noo total number of occurrences per species

First notes

  • Mean latitude and minimum latitude are strongly correlated, one of them probably has to be removed from the model
  • Grid cells, GCD and latitudinal range are correlated
  • Geo distribution and habitat width seem positively correlated
  • Grid cells correlate positively with duration
  • Body size increase decreases duration
  • Body size seems bigger in small habitat widths?
  • Body size increase decreases geo ranges?
  • More habitats increase duration (see boxplot)
  • Min + mean latitude increase with habitat width (northern hemisphere seems to have larger habitat widths)
  • Lat range, GDC and grid cells seem larger in northern hemisphere

Body size and geo range follow patterns we observe today as well. Abundance seems to be a difficult one. Checking for preservation/sampling bias: why there is larger habitat widths and also ranges in the northern hemisphere, and why should big species occupy only one habitat type?

The median durations between habitat width groups (1,2,3) differ significantly, although category 4 just has one single count and therefore cannot be considered. Removing all singe-interval species does not influence this pattern. There is a positive correlation (apparently non monotonous as stronger using spearmans rank correlation) between number of occurrences and number of habitat types. The resason is obvious to some degree, as the number of habitats is required as minimum number of occurrences for each habitat width. Regarding preservation probability, the number of occurrences simply could be the reason for the observed pattern between duration and habitat width as it potentially influences both duration and habitat width. However, correcting the habitat width for the number of occurrences in each species does not seem justified as this would exclude the possibility of species just being more abundant as well as it would excessively punish very abundant species. E.g. Opisthotriton kayi with 71 occurrences in 3 habitat types would end up having a lower habitat width index than a species occurring in just one habitat with 3 occurrenes. Being rare would let species appear to occupy in more habitats.

Might these differences be caused by larger sample size in the northern hemisphere?

If habitat width appears larger with bigger latitudes (north), this might be a result of a more comprehensive fossil record in the northern hemisphere. There is two factors: more occurrences in the north, and also more species in the north. Recalculating the habitat widths for the northern hemisphere species, using the same amount of occurrences like found in the southern hemisphere, then correlating the new habitat width again with mean latitude, is likely to show if sampling or preservation bias causes the effect. Based on the occurrence data underlying the species based dataset, I resampled the data and calculated for each set (500) the habitat width for each species, this way simluating a dataset with equally distributed occurrences between northern and southern hemisphere.

The original and bootstraped habitat widths are strongly correlated. However, there is no correlation between habitat width and latitude any longer when using bootstraped values - this indicates that the regional effect I observe in the habitat width is caused by simply more occurrences in the northern hemisphere and therefore higher chance of observing larger values.

When performing bootstrap on the data again, this time to match number of species between both hemispheres:

stat <- c()
p.stat <- c()
south <- dat[dat$mean_lat<0,]
north <- dat[dat$mean_lat>=0,]
for(i in 1:1000){
  temp.n <- north[sample(c(1:nrow(north)), nrow(south)),]
  temp <- rbind(temp.n, south)
  res <- cor.test(temp$mean_lat, temp$hab_w_boot, method="spearman")
  stat <- c(stat, res$estimate[[1]])
  p.stat <- c(p.stat, res$p.value[[1]])
  i <- i+1
}
hist(stat, breaks=20, xlab="rho", main="distribution or rho from bootstrap")
abline(v=cor.test(dat$mean_lat, dat$hab_w_boot, method="spearman")$estimate[[1]], col="red")

Repeated subsampling without replacement of northern hemisphere species by the number of the southern hemisphere species gives a mean correlation between mean latitude and habitat width of 0.03 (mad=0.05 ), with 0.02 being significantly correlated. As the correlation lies well within 2 standard deviations of the distribution, there is no evidence that the differing number of species influences the interaction of the parameters. Same is true when performing the test on the original data, only that in this case correlation remains when bootstrapping for species numbers (not shown).

There seems to be no reason however to alter the dataset by subsampling if estimating the influence of habitat width on duration, as the differences in occurrences affects duration and habitat in the same way.

[Have to do bootstrap on occurrences for geo range] Repeated subsampling without replacement of northern hemisphere species by the number of the southern hemisphere species gives a median correlation between mean latitude and grid cells of 0.11 (mad=0.03 ), with 0.29 being significantly correlated. As the correlation lies well within 2 median average deviations of the distribution, the influence of the more intense sampling of the northern hemisphere on the correlation between mean latitude and geographic distribution in number of grid cells can be neglected.

For the model, same reasoning applies as for the habitat width. Bootstrapping geographic range size to remove a latitudinal trend caused by occurence number is not necessary, as this affects duration and geographic range in the same way. Maybe more important: I am not interested in regional differences.

Data exploration following Zuur, Ieno, Walker, Saveliev, and Smith (2009)

A basic linear model

lm3 <- lm(data=dat, ma_range ~ mni_max + spec_max + grid_cells + gcd + lat_range + 
            mean_lat + min_lat + asl_pred + hab.cat.b + habitat_width + hab_w_boot + noo) 
op <- par(mfrow=c(4,4), mar=c(5,4,1,2))
plot(lm3, add.smooth = FALSE, which=1)
hist(resid(lm3), xlab="Residuals", main="", breaks=20)
plot(dat$mni_max[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$spec_max[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$grid_cells[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$gcd[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$lat_range[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$mean_lat[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$min_lat[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$asl_pred[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$hab.cat.b[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")

plot(dat$hab_w_boot[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
plot(dat$noo[as.numeric(names(resid(lm3)))], resid(lm3), ylab="Residuals")
par(op)

Assumptions for linear model: normality, homogeneity, fixed X, independence.

Variables not to use: one latidinal indicator, one of the abundance variables, number of occurrences. Might want to use latitudinal range instead of grid cells as it`s less correlated with the habitat varaibles. Also easier to compare to extant species (no shape file area to grid cell count required).

Bartlett test is sensitive to non-normality.

op <- par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar=c(5,4,1,2))
plot(lm3)

par(op)

There is a patter in the spread of residuals, so homogeneity not given. Residuals vs.leverage shows potentially influential observations. There is no cook distance larger 1, no action required (Zuur, Ieno, Walker, et al. (2009)).

Homogeneity can be handled by allowing for different variances with generalised least squares estimation, or by using a different model structure: poisson, neg binomial etc. Dependence can be handled with smoothing.

Chosing a model following Zuur, Ieno, Walker, et al. (2009)

Smoothing model (additive models (GAM))

Allows for non-linear interaction between response and multiple explanatoy variables. gam or mgcv packages in R, gam is easier, mgcv provides cross validation, nested data and various heterogeneity patterns.

Allowing for different variances using GLS (heterogeneity)

# gls cannot handle missing values therefor I have to create a subdataset with complete observations only
dat.m <- na.omit(dat[,c("ma_range", "mni_max", "grid_cells", "mean_lat", "asl_pred",
                        "hab.cat.b", "hab_w_boot", "order")])

library(nlme)
Form <- formula(ma_range ~ mni_max + grid_cells + mean_lat + asl_pred +
              hab.cat.b + hab_w_boot)
gls1 <- gls(data=dat.m, Form)

vf1Comb <- varComb(varExp(form= ~ asl_pred), 
                   varExp(form= ~ grid_cells),
                   varPower(form= ~ mean_lat),
                   varConstPower(form= ~ mni_max),
                   varPower(form= ~ hab_w_boot))
# the best combination of adjusting for varying variances

gls2 <- gls(data=dat.m, Form, weights = vf1Comb, method="REML")

Nested data?

Also: there might be some deviation from constant variance assumption (residuals~fitted values), there seem to be 3 outliers in the data (normal-q-q plot: 9,61, 146). Residuals are getting larger with values getting larger, with one clear outlier. ### Mulitcolinearity min_lat and mean_lat are strongly correlated, so assumptions are violated here. According to wikipedia, Multicollinearity does not reduce the predictive power or reliability of the model as a whole, at least within the sample data set; it only affects calculations regarding individual predictors. That is, a multiple regression model with correlated predictors can indicate how well the entire bundle of predictors predicts the outcome variable, but it may not give valid results about any individual predictor, or about which predictors are redundant with respect to others. This is especially strange as removing one of the correlated variables results in a stark drop of R squared. For colinerarity, correlation needs to be linear.

Conclusion

The linear model explains around 30% of the observed data, however it suffers from multicolinearity between mean and minimum latitude. This makes estimates for predictor coeffiecients less precise and potentially roduces type 2 errors. Removing one of these factors however reduces explained variance dramatically. Logging the dependent variable seems appropriate, given that the outcome variable is highly skewed.

Generalized linear model (GLM)

The generalized linear model uses a poisson distribution as a proxy for a negative binomial function.

# pseudo r^2
R2logit<- function(model){
    R2<- 1-(model$deviance/model$null.deviance)
    return(R2)
}

Zero-Inflated model

Worth a try as the data includes lots of zeros, some of them might be produced by preservation bias instead of being real.

library(pscl)
f1 <- formula(as.integer(ma_range)~ mni_max + grid_cells + asl_pred + lat_range + mean_lat + min_lat) # + hab.cat.b
zi1 <- zeroinfl(f1, dist="negbin", link="logit", data=dat.m)
summary(zi1)

Generalized boosted model

This is a machine learning technique. Models are quite immune to overfitting and can also deal with correlations of variables. Sounds promising! GBM also handles missing data, not sure yet what this means in detail though.
